.TH NINA 1 "2026" "nina" "User Commands"

.SH NAME
nina - command-line personal knowledge management system

.SH SYNOPSIS
.B nina
.RI [ OPTION ] " [ARGUMENT]"

.br
.B nina
.br
.B nina
"Article Title"

.SH DESCRIPTION
.B nina
is a command-line personal knowledge management system that stores all
content as Markdown files on the filesystem.

The program provides tools to create, browse, search, and analyze a
personal knowledge base while preserving the user's direct control
over their data. Articles are stored as plain text files and may be
edited with any standard text editor.

The system maintains an index file to enable fast searches and queries.
This index is derived data and may be rebuilt at any time from the
Markdown files.

Running
.B nina
with no arguments displays a list of all indexed articles.

If the first argument does not match a command option, it is treated
as an article title and the article will be rendered in the terminal.

.SH ARTICLE FORMAT
Each article is stored as a Markdown file beginning with a simple
metadata header:

.nf

# Article Title

* Author: Name
* Tags: tag1 tag2 tag3
* Date: YYYY-MM-DD
.fi

Only the title line is required. All other fields are optional.

The remainder of the file contains standard Markdown text.

.SH OPTIONS

.TP
.BR -n ", " --new " TITLE"
Create a new article with the specified title and open it in the
configured text editor.

.TP
.BR -s ", " --search " QUERY"
Search the full text of all articles - titles and body
content - for the given query, and list matching articles
ranked by relevance. The query may be one or more words.
Matching is case-insensitive and ignores punctuation
differences.

Results are ranked so that articles where the query words
appear close together, in a title, or in a heading rank
above articles where the words are far apart or scattered
across different sentences. This ranking is a deliberate,
useful approximation rather than a strict literal match;
it is still fully deterministic (the same query over the
same knowledge base always produces the same ordering).

.RS
.TP
.B --count
Print only the number of matching articles.
.TP
.B --explain
Show the relevance score alongside each result. Useful for
understanding why articles are ranked as they are.
.RE

.TP
.BR -t ", " --tag
Display a list of all tags in the knowledge base.

.TP
.BR -t ", " --tag " TAG"
List articles associated with the specified tag.

.TP
.BR -d ", " --date " RANGE"
List articles filtered by modification date.

Supported formats include:

.nf
YYYY
YYYY-MM
YYYY-MM-DD
START..END
DATE+N
.fi

Examples:

.nf
nina --date 2026
nina --date 2026-03
nina --date 2026-03-10
nina --date 2026-03-01..2026-03-31
nina --date 2026-03-10+7
.fi

.TP
.BR -b ", " --backlinks " TITLE"
Display articles that link to the specified article.

.TP
.BR -l ", " --links " TITLE"
Display articles linked from the specified article.

.TP
.BR -r ", " --random
Open a random article.

.TP
.BR --read " FILE"
Render an arbitrary text file through the same rendering engine used
for articles, without consulting the index. The file need not be
part of the knowledge base, be named with a
.B .md
extension, or contain a metadata header; plain text simply renders
with no styling applied. If
.I FILE
is omitted and data is piped in instead (or piped into
.B nina
with no arguments at all), the piped stream is rendered the same way.
Editing while viewing is supported either way, but piped data has no
file behind it - if it is edited and saved, you will be prompted for
a destination before the edit is discarded.

.PP
When piped data is edited and saved to a
.I different
path than the original buffer (a "save as" inside the editor),
.B less
has no way to learn this and will continue displaying the original,
unchanged buffer rather than the newly saved file. The edit is not
lost - it exists at the path you saved it to - but it will not be
shown until you run
.B nina --read
again on that path directly. Editing and saving in place does not
have this limitation.

.TP
.BR --orphan
List articles that are not referenced by any other article.

.TP
.BR --orphan " --count"
Display only the number of orphan articles.

.TP
.BR --dangling
List links that reference articles that do not exist.

.TP
.BR --dangling " --count"
Display only the number of dangling links.

.TP
.BR --graph
Output a graph representation of article links suitable for Graphviz.

.TP
.BR --stats
Display statistics describing the knowledge base.

.TP
.BR -i ", " --index
Rebuild the article index from the Markdown files.

.TP
.BR --remove " [\"ARTICLE TITLE\"]"
Remove an article.
If
.I "ARTICLE TITLE"
is omitted, a numbered list of all articles is displayed for selection.

The action taken is controlled by
.B REMOVE_MODE
in the configuration file:
.BR archive ,
.BR delete ,
or
.BR choose
(prompt at runtime). See
.BR nina.conf (5).

If the given title does not match any article, similar titles are
suggested.

.TP
.BR --repair
Run interactive tools that assist in repairing common problems such
as duplicate titles or malformed metadata.

.TP
.BR --restore
Restore an article from the archive.

.TP
.BR --resync
Compare each article's title against its filename and list any
mismatches. Renaming is interactive and one article at a time;
select a number to rename it to the program's expected filename,
or press
.B Enter
to exit. This command does not rebuild the index; run
.B nina --index
afterward.


.TP
.BR -D ", " --doctor
Run diagnostics on the knowledge base and configuration.

.TP
.BR --config
Display the current configuration file.

.TP
.BR --config " --edit"
Open the configuration file in the configured editor.

.TP
.BR --config " --validate"
Validate the configuration file.

.TP
.BR --config " --reset"
Back up the current configuration file and replace it with the
default configuration.
Requires typing
.B reset
to confirm.

.TP
.BR --macro
Install custom macros for use in
.B {{...}}
expansions (see MARKUP LANGUAGE, Macros in
.BR nina.conf (5)).
Scans
.B MACROS_DIR
for macro files, validates each one, and installs whichever
macros pass validation. This command is never interactive and
never repairs a macro file - it only decides which macros nina
will load, and reports the filename and reason for anything it
rejects. Most users will not need this command unless they are
installing a macro someone else wrote, or writing their own.
Run it after adding, removing, or editing a macro file; macros
are not re-validated every time an article is rendered.

.TP
.BR --plugin
Install custom plugins for use in
.B <<...>>
expansions (see MARKUP LANGUAGE, Plugins in
.BR nina.conf (5)).
Scans
.B PLUGINS_DIR
for plugin files, validates each one, and installs whichever
plugins pass validation. This command is never interactive and
never repairs a plugin file - it only decides which plugins nina
will load, and reports the filename and reason for anything it
rejects. Plugins are a more powerful and less restricted
mechanism than macros: a plugin may read other articles in the
knowledge base and, if explicitly permitted, reach the network.
See SECURITY CONSIDERATIONS in
.BR nina.conf (5)
before installing a plugin written by someone else. Run this
command after adding, removing, or editing a plugin file;
plugins are not re-validated every time an article is rendered.

.SH INTERACTIVE NAVIGATION
Many commands display numbered result lists.

Entering a number will open the corresponding article.

Press
.B Enter
to exit without opening an article.

.SH FILES

.TP
.I ~/.nina/config
User configuration file.

.TP
.I ~/.nina/index.tsv
Generated metadata index.

.TP
.I ~/.nina/macros/
Default directory for macro files. See
.BR nina.conf (5).

.TP
.I ~/.nina/macros.tsv
Generated list of macros that passed validation. Rewritten
each time
.B --macro
is run; not intended to be edited by hand.

.TP
.I ~/.nina/macros-dispatch.awk
Generated macro dispatch logic, derived from
.IR ~/.nina/macros.tsv .
Rewritten each time
.B --macro
is run; not intended to be edited by hand.

.TP
.I ~/.nina/plugins/
Default directory for plugin files. See
.BR nina.conf (5).

.TP
.I ~/.nina/plugins.tsv
Generated list of plugins that passed validation, including
whether each one is permitted the longer of the two plugin
timeouts. Rewritten each time
.B --plugin
is run; not intended to be edited by hand.

.TP
.I ~/nina/
Default directory containing article Markdown files.

.TP
.I ~/nina/archive/
Archive directory used when removing articles.

.SH EXIT STATUS
Most commands use a simple convention:

.TP
.B 0
Success.

.TP
.B 1
An error occurred (e.g. article not found, invalid usage).

.PP
.BR --doctor
is an exception and uses a three-tier convention reflecting the
most severe issue found:

.TP
.B 0
No problems found.

.TP
.B 1
One or more warnings were found, but no errors.

.TP
.B 2
One or more errors were found.







.SH EXAMPLES

Create a new article:

.nf
nina --new "Project Ideas"
.fi

Open an article:

.nf
nina "Project Ideas"
.fi

List all articles in the knowledge base:

.nf
nina
.fi

Search articles by content:

.nf
nina --search database
.fi

Filter articles by tag:

.nf
nina --tag research
.fi

List articles modified during a specific month:

.nf
nina --date 2026-03
.fi

List articles modified during a date range:

.nf
nina --date 2026-03-01..2026-03-31
.fi

List articles modified within a number of days of a date:

.nf
nina --date 2026-03-10+7
.fi

Show articles that link to a page:

.nf
nina --backlinks "Neural Networks"
.fi

Show links contained within an article:

.nf
nina --links "Neural Networks"
.fi

List orphaned articles (not referenced by other pages):

.nf
nina --orphan
.fi

Count orphaned articles:

.nf
nina --orphan --count
.fi

List dangling links (links pointing to missing articles):

.nf
nina --dangling
.fi

Count dangling links:

.nf
nina --dangling --count
.fi

Open a random article:

.nf
nina --random
.fi

Render a file that is not part of the knowledge base:

.nf
nina --read notes.txt
.fi

Render piped data:

.nf
cat draft.md | nina --read
.fi

Rebuild the article index:

.nf
nina --index
.fi

Run system diagnostics:

.nf
nina --doctor
.fi

Repair duplicate titles or invalid metadata:

.nf
nina --repair
.fi

Find and fix filenames that no longer match their article's title:

.nf
nina --resync
.fi

Remove an article:

.nf
nina --remove "Old Notes"
.fi

Restore an article from the archive:

.nf
nina --restore
.fi

Export the link graph for visualization with Graphviz:

.nf
nina --graph > graph.dot
dot -Tpng graph.dot -o nina_graph.png
.fi

Install a custom macro after adding it to
.BR MACROS_DIR :

.nf
nina --macro
.fi

Install a custom plugin after adding it to
.BR PLUGINS_DIR :

.nf
nina --plugin
.fi

.SH DESIGN NOTES

The design of
.B nina
follows several principles intended to keep the system reliable,
transparent, and easy to maintain.

.PP
Plain text storage
.RS
All articles are stored as Markdown files on the filesystem.
The files can be opened, edited, moved, or copied using standard tools
without requiring the
.B nina
program itself.
.RE

.PP
Filesystem as the source of truth
.RS
The Markdown files represent the canonical state of the knowledge base.
Supporting files such as the metadata index are derived data and can
always be rebuilt.
.RE

.PP
Derived data is disposable
.RS
The file
.I index.tsv
contains metadata extracted from the articles to accelerate queries.
If the index becomes invalid or is deleted, it can be regenerated by
running:

.nf
nina --index
.fi
.RE

.PP
Small tools and simple scripts
.RS
The program is implemented as a collection of small scripts that perform
well-defined tasks. This design keeps the code readable and reduces the
complexity of individual components.
.RE

.PP
Minimal dependencies
.RS
The system intentionally avoids heavy libraries or complex frameworks.
The goal is to remain portable across typical UNIX environments and to
work reliably on minimal systems.
.RE

.PP
Graceful degradation
.RS
Problems such as duplicate titles, malformed metadata, or missing
articles should not render the system unusable. Instead the program
attempts to continue operating while reporting warnings and providing
tools such as
.B --doctor
and
.B --repair
to help resolve issues.
.RE

.PP
User control of data
.RS
The program avoids modifying article files unless explicitly requested.
Users retain full control over their Markdown documents and may edit
them using any text editor.
.RE

.PP
UNIX-style command behavior
.RS
Commands are driven by flags, output is text-based, and results can be
piped into other utilities. The program is intended to behave like other
traditional command-line tools.
.RE










.SH WORKFLOW

A typical workflow using
.B nina
may look like the following.

.PP
Create a new article when capturing information:

.nf
nina --new "Distributed Systems Notes"
.fi

.PP
Edit the article using the configured editor and add links to other
articles using nina-style link syntax.

.PP
Open articles directly by title:

.nf
nina "Distributed Systems Notes"
.fi

.PP
Search for related topics:

.nf
nina --search consensus
.fi

.PP
Browse articles by tag:

.nf
nina --tag distributed
.fi

.PP
Navigate through linked articles using numbered selections when
viewing results.

.PP
Periodically rebuild the index if many articles have been added
or modified:

.nf
nina --index
.fi

.PP
Use diagnostic tools to inspect the health of the knowledge base:

.nf
nina --doctor
.fi

.PP
Repair problems such as duplicate titles or malformed metadata:

.nf
nina --repair
.fi

.PP
Over time the knowledge base becomes a network of Markdown files
connected by links, searchable by tags and dates, and accessible
directly from the command line.

.SH TROUBLESHOOTING

The following commands can help diagnose and repair common problems.

.TP
Index file missing or out of date

If commands fail due to a missing or outdated index, rebuild it:

.nf
nina --index
.fi

.TP
Duplicate article titles

Article titles must be unique. Duplicate titles will be skipped during
indexing.

To locate and repair duplicate titles:

.nf
nina --doctor
nina --repair
.fi

.TP
Articles not appearing in search results

If newly created articles do not appear in listings, rebuild the index:

.nf
nina --index
.fi

.TP
Broken links

Links that point to missing articles can be identified with:

.nf
nina --dangling
.fi

These links can be fixed either by editing the article or by creating
the missing page.

.TP
Orphan articles

Articles that are not referenced by any other article can be listed
with:

.nf
nina --orphan
.fi

These pages may represent isolated notes or forgotten topics.

.TP
Configuration errors

If the configuration file contains syntax errors or missing settings:

.nf
nina --config --validate
.fi

.TP
Unexpected behavior

Run system diagnostics to check the environment, index integrity, and
article metadata:

.nf
nina --doctor
.fi

.PP
Because all article data is stored as Markdown files, users can always
inspect or edit the files directly using standard tools if necessary.








.SH HISTORY

The
.B nina
program was developed as a command-line knowledge management tool
designed around the principles of plain text storage and UNIX-style
tool behavior.

.PP
Many personal knowledge systems rely on graphical interfaces,
databases, or proprietary storage formats. While these systems may
provide advanced features, they can make it difficult for users to
retain direct control over their data.

.PP
The design of
.B nina
takes a different approach. Articles are stored as ordinary Markdown
files on the filesystem, allowing them to be edited with any text
editor and managed using standard command-line tools.

.PP
The program provides indexing, navigation, and analysis tools that
operate on these files while preserving the user's ownership of the
underlying data.

.PP
This design reflects several long-standing UNIX traditions:

.RS
.IP (bu
Plain text data formats
.IP (bu
Programs that do one job well
.IP (bu
Tools that compose naturally with other utilities
.IP (bu
Minimal dependencies and predictable behavior
.RE

.PP
By combining these principles with a lightweight Markdown-based
knowledge base, the system aims to provide a durable and transparent
tool for organizing personal information in a terminal environment.

















